### Area

testsuite

### Describe the bug

InstallationTest can fail depending on test method ordering.

Here is an example where attributes are added to the client with rollback:
https://github.com/keycloak/keycloak/blob/4c7d6f954f5d0e40ed96bf3f38e0a02c406fe864/tests/base/src/test/java/org/keycloak/tests/admin/client/InstallationTest.java#L330-L335

Problem is that when updating the client to the original representation only changed attributes are updated, removed attributes are ignored.

### Version

main

### Regression

- [ ] The issue is a regression

### Expected behavior

Attributes added with rollback should be removed

### Actual behavior

Attributes added with rollback are not removed

### How to Reproduce?

Use the reproducer below. When running the test you can see that attribute `one` is reset to `one`, but attribute `two` remains.

```
package org.keycloak.tests.admin.client;

import org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions;
import org.junit.jupiter.api.MethodOrderer;
import org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;
import org.junit.jupiter.api.TestMethodOrder;
import org.keycloak.representations.idm.ClientRepresentation;
import org.keycloak.testframework.annotations.InjectClient;
import org.keycloak.testframework.annotations.KeycloakIntegrationTest;
import org.keycloak.testframework.realm.ClientConfig;
import org.keycloak.testframework.realm.ClientConfigBuilder;
import org.keycloak.testframework.realm.ManagedClient;

@KeycloakIntegrationTest
@TestMethodOrder(MethodOrderer.MethodName.class)
public class ClientConfigTest {

    @InjectClient(config = MyClient.class)
    ManagedClient client;

    @Test
    public void testAddAttributeWithRollback() {
        client.updateWithCleanup(u -> u.attribute("one", "two").attribute("two", "two"));

        ClientRepresentation rep = client.admin().toRepresentation();
        Assertions.assertEquals("two", rep.getAttributes().get("one"));
        Assertions.assertTrue(rep.getAttributes().containsKey("two"));
    }

    @Test
    public void testAttributeNotSet() {
        ClientRepresentation rep = client.admin().toRepresentation();
        Assertions.assertEquals("one", rep.getAttributes().get("one"));
        Assertions.assertFalse(rep.getAttributes().containsKey("two"));
    }

    public static class MyClient implements ClientConfig {
        @Override
        public ClientConfigBuilder configure(ClientConfigBuilder client) {
            return client.attribute("one", "one");
        }
    }
}
```

